</row>

<row>
<cell>Let r and <m>\theta</m>be polar coordinates of the point (x, y) of the complex number z = x+iy. Since x = <m>r\text{cos}\theta</m>and y = <m>r\text{sin}\theta</m>, then the complex number can be written as : <m>\underline{\underline{\ z = r(\text{cos}\theta + i\text{sin}\theta)}}</m> which is called polar form, where r is modulus of z and <m>\ \theta\ </m>is principal argument of z.</cell>
</row>
